Read this slowly.
There is a version of you writing Angular code right now.
And there is a better version of you who knows exactly what to avoid, when to refactor, and how to write code that looks senior, intentional, and clean.
The gap between those two versions is not years.
It is knowledge.
Real, field-tested knowledge.
When I started with Angular, I thought learning components, routing, services, and modules meant I understood the framework.
I was wrong.
The real growth started when I learned the techniques no one teaches early.
The techniques hidden in conference talks, code reviews, and mentorship sessions.
Today, I am handing them to you, without the years of trial and error.
Let us begin.
1. Using Signals Instead of Overusing Subjects
Before:
count$ = new BehaviorSubject(0);
increase() {
this.count$.next(this.count$.value + 1);
}After:
count = signal(0);
increase() {
this.count.update(v => v + 1);
}
